Fig. 6
 gives the excitation and emission spectra for CDs-1, CDs-2, CDs-3 and CDs-4. The maximum excitation wavelength for CDs-1 was centered at 360 nm, and its maximum emission wavelength was centered at 405 nm. The pyrolysis of 2, 4, 6-trihydroxybenzoic acid might not complete at 180 °C for 2 h with SnCl4 as a catalyst. Compared with those for CDs-1, the maximum excitation wavelength for CDs-2 shifted to 466 nm, and its maximum emission wavelength red shifted to 545 nm. Moreover, the absolute quantum yield increased 3.62 times compared with that for CDs-1 (Table 1
). The reason was attributed to that the pyrolysis of 2, 4, 6-trihydroxybenzoic acid could be efficiently catalyzed by the SnO2 NPs which were formed in the one–step reaction with n-butylamine as a base. More interface defect states were produced on the interface of CDs-2, as a result, the excitation spectrum for CDs-2 shifted to the visible region of 400–500 nm, and the maximum emission wavelength of CDs-2 red shifted 140 nm. In the absence of SnCl4 as a catalyst, weak yellow color was observed for CDs-3 with 2, 4, 6-trihydroxybenzoic acid as carbon source and with m-phenylenediamine as nitrogen source. The absolute quantum yield for CDs-3 was only 40% of that for CDs-1, the results showed that SnCl4 had some catalysis for pyrolysis of 2, 4, 6-trihydroxybenzoic acid. The color for CDs-3 red shifted 153 nm compared with that for CDs-1, it was attributed to the doping of nitrogen atoms in CDs-3 with m-phenylenediamine as nitrogen source. Bright yellow emission for CDs-4 was obtained with SnO2 NPs as a catalyst which was formed in the one-step hydrolysis of SnCl4 with m-phenylenediamine as both a base and nitrogen source. The absolute quantum yield for CDs-4 was increased to 38% with SnO2 NPs as a catalyst. The yield value for CDs-4 was c. a. 22 times of that for CDs-3, and the yield for CDs-4 increased c. a. 9 times of that for CDs-1 (Table 1). The results showed that the pyrolysis of 2, 4, 6-trihydroxybenzoic acid and m-phenylenediamine could be efficiently catalyzed by SnO2 NPs. The catalysis of SnO2 NPs for pyrolysis of 2, 4, 6-trihydroxybenzoic acid was greater than that of SnCl4. The SnO2 NPs could be easily removed by centrifugation, and the SnCl4 could be separated by dialysis to ensure the purity of the CDs. The XPS data for CDs-4 showed that Sn element was completely removed by centrifugation.
